So, you want to know about the study of computation. Fine. Don't expect me to hold your hand through it. It's a vast, often infuriating landscape, and frankly, most people who wander into it are ill-equipped. But if you insist on wading through the muck, here’s what you need to know.

## Study of Computation

### Fundamental Areas of Computer Science

Before we even begin to dissect the mechanics of it all, understand that computer science isn't just about the blinking lights and whirring fans. It's fundamentally about [computation](/Computation), [information](/Information), and the relentless pursuit of [automation](/Automation). It’s a sprawling field, touching upon the most abstract corners of thought and the most concrete applications of engineering.

*   **[Programming language theory](/Programming_language_theory)**: This is where we wrestle with how we tell machines what to do. It’s about the syntax, the semantics, the very essence of communication between human intent and silicon execution. It’s less about the *how* of writing code and more about the *why* and the fundamental properties of the languages we invent.
*   **[Computer architecture](/Computer_architecture)**: This is the guts of it. The blueprint of the machine itself. How do you design the circuits, the memory, the processors to handle the sheer torrent of data? It’s about the physical realization of abstract thought.
*   **[Artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence)**: The grand ambition, or perhaps the ultimate folly. Can we make machines *think*? Or at least mimic it well enough to fool us? It’s about learning, problem-solving, decision-making – all the messy, complex processes we associate with intelligence, distilled into algorithms.
*   **[Computational complexity theory](/Computational_complexity_theory)**: This is where we confront the limits. Not just *if* something can be computed, but *how efficiently*. How much time, how much space, how much sheer effort will it take? It’s the grim reality check for every elegant algorithm.

It’s a field with a rich [history](/History_of_computer_science), an intricate [outline](/Outline_of_computer_science), and a glossary that’s perpetually expanding. And if you’re lost, well, that’s what the [Category:Computer_science](/Category:Computer_science) is for.

### Core Concepts

At its heart, computer science is the study of [computation](/Computation), [information](/Information), and [automation](/Automation). It’s a branch of [the sciences](/Science), but one that straddles the line between the purely theoretical and the intensely practical. You've got your [theoretical disciplines](/Theoretical_computer_science) – the elegant, abstract realms of [algorithms](/Algorithm), [theory of computation](/Theory_of_computation), and [information theory](/Information_theory) – and then you have the applied side, the messy business of actually building [hardware](/Computer_architecture) and crafting [software](/Software_engineering). An expert in this domain, if such a thing truly exists, is called a [computer scientist](/Computer_scientist).

Central to this entire endeavor are [algorithms](/Algorithm) and [data structures](/Data_structure). They are the building blocks, the fundamental tools that a computer scientist wields. Without them, you’re just staring at a pile of metal and plastic.

The [theory of computation](/Theory_of_computation) delves into the abstract [models of computation](/Models_of_computation) and the boundaries of what [problems](/Computational_problem) can actually be solved. It’s here that you'll find fields like [cryptography](/Cryptography) and [computer security](/Computer_security), where the intricate dance of secure communication and the perpetual battle against [security vulnerabilities](/Security_vulnerabilities) takes place. Then there’s [computer graphics](/Computer_graphics_(computer_science)) and [computational geometry](/Computational_geometry), the art and science of conjuring images from pure data. [Programming language theory](/Programming_language_theory) dissects the ways we express computational processes, while [database](/Database) theory grapples with the monumental task of organizing and retrieving vast oceans of information.

We also examine the human element with [human–computer interaction](/Human%E2%80%93computer_interaction), trying to bridge the gap between our messy biology and the cold logic of machines. [Software engineering](/Software_engineering) focuses on the rigorous principles behind building reliable software. And we can’t forget the complex systems: [operating systems](/Operating_system), [networks](/Computer_network), [embedded systems](/Embedded_system) – the intricate ecosystems that make everything *work*. Finally, [computer architecture](/Computer_architecture) is the study of how these machines are physically constructed, the very bones and sinews of the digital world.

And then there’s [artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence) and [machine learning](/Machine_learning). The grand attempt to replicate, or at least simulate, the goal-oriented processes of life: problem-solving, decision-making, adaptation, [planning](/Automated_planning_and_scheduling), and learning. Within AI, [computer vision](/Computer_vision) seeks to understand the world through images, while [natural language processing](/Natural_language_processing) tries to decipher our words.

Ultimately, the core obsession of computer science is this: what can and cannot be automated? &#91;2&#93; &#91;8&#93; &#91;3&#93; &#91;9&#93; &#91;10&#93; It’s a question that drives innovation and, occasionally, existential dread. And for those who truly master this domain, the [Turing Award](/Turing_Award) is the ultimate, if often belated, recognition. &#91;11&#93; &#91;12&#93;

## History

### History of Computer Science

*   Main article: [History of computer science](/History_of_computer_science)
*   See also: [History of computing](/History_of_computing)

The foundations of what we now call computer science were laid long before the first silicon chip flickered to life. Calculating devices, rudimentary as they were, have existed since antiquity – the [abacus](/Abacus) being a prime example, aiding in the drudgery of multiplication and division. But even before the machines, there were the [algorithms](/Algorithm), the step-by-step instructions for performing computations, a practice as old as organized thought itself. &#91;16&#93;

The real mechanical lineage begins in 1623 with [Wilhelm Schickard](/Wilhelm_Schickard) and his calculator. &#91;17&#93; Then, in 1673, [Gottfried Leibniz](/Gottfried_Leibniz) unveiled his [Stepped Reckoner](/Stepped_Reckoner), a digital mechanical calculator. &#91;18&#93; Leibniz, with his work on [logic](/Logic) and the [binary number](/Binary_number) system, is often hailed as a progenitor of the field, a true pioneer. &#91;13&#93; By 1820, [Thomas de Colmar](/Thomas_de_Colmar) had industrialized calculation with his [arithmometer](/Arithmometer), a machine robust enough for daily office use.

But the true visionary, the one who truly grasped the potential of programmable machines, was [Charles Babbage](/Charles_Babbage). In 1822, he began work on his [Difference Engine](/Difference_Engine), a complex mechanical calculator. This, however, was merely a stepping stone to his grander, more ambitious [Analytical Engine](/Analytical_Engine), conceived around 1834. &#91;19&#93; This was a machine with a central processing unit, memory, and the crucial innovation: programmability, largely thanks to the adoption of punched cards, inspired by the [Jacquard loom](/Jacquard_loom). &#91;20&#93; It was during the translation of an article on this very engine that [Ada Lovelace](/Ada_Lovelace) penned what is considered the first algorithm intended for machine execution, a method for calculating [Bernoulli numbers](/Bernoulli_number), in 1843. &#91;21&#93;

Later, in 1885, [Herman Hollerith](/Herman_Hollerith) developed his [tabulator](/Tabulating_machine), a punched-card system for processing statistical data, which eventually laid the groundwork for [IBM](/IBM). Even in the early 20th century, the spirit of Babbage’s ideas lived on. [Percy Ludgate](/Percy_Ludgate) designed a mechanical analytical engine in 1909, &#91;22&#93; and [Leonardo Torres Quevedo](/Leonardo_Torres_Quevedo) proposed an electromechanical calculating machine controlled by a read-only program, even introducing the concept of [floating-point arithmetic](/Floating-point_arithmetic). &#91;23&#93; &#91;24&#93; &#91;25&#93; By 1937, [Howard Aiken](/Howard_Aiken), inspired by Babbage's work, convinced IBM to develop the [ASCC/Harvard Mark I](/Harvard_Mark_I), a colossal programmable calculator that many hailed as Babbage's dream realized. &#91;29&#93;

The 1940s marked a seismic shift. Machines like the [Atanasoff–Berry computer](/Atanasoff%E2%80%93Berry_computer) and the [ENIAC](/ENIAC) emerged, and the term "computer" began to refer to the machines themselves, not the humans who operated them. &#91;30&#93; As these machines grew more powerful and versatile, the field of computer science expanded beyond mere calculation to encompass the broader study of [computation](/Computation). IBM’s establishment of the [Watson Scientific Computing Laboratory](/Watson_Scientific_Computing_Laboratory) at [Columbia University](/Columbia_University) in 1945 signaled a growing academic interest. &#91;31&#93; By 1946, Columbia was offering one of the first academic courses in computer science, &#91;32&#93; and by the 1950s and early 60s, it was solidifying its place as a distinct academic discipline. &#91;33&#93; &#91;34&#93; The [Cambridge Diploma in Computer Science](/Cambridge_Diploma_in_Computer_Science) at the [University of Cambridge Computer Laboratory](/University_of_Cambridge_Computer_Laboratory) began in 1953, and the first dedicated department in the United States was founded at [Purdue University](/Purdue_University) in 1962. &#91;35&#93;

### Etymology and Scope

The term "computer science" itself, though first proposed in 1956, didn't gain traction until a 1959 article in [Communications of the ACM](/Communications_of_the_ACM). &#91;37&#93; Louis Fein argued for its establishment as a formal discipline, likening its applied and interdisciplinary nature to that of [management science](/Management_science). &#91;38&#93; This, along with the efforts of figures like [George Forsythe](/George_Forsythe), paved the way for departments like Purdue's in 1962. &#91;39&#93;

But here's the rub: the name is a bit of a misnomer. A significant portion of computer science has little to do with the physical computers themselves. This ambiguity has led to alternative terms. Some universities opt for "computing science" to highlight this distinction. The Danish scientist [Peter Naur](/Peter_Naur) proposed "datalogi" (or datalogy), emphasizing the study of data and its manipulation, rather than the machines. &#91;41&#93; He also suggested "[data science](/Data_science)", a term now widely used for the interdisciplinary field of data analysis.

Historically, the naming of practitioners was a bit more whimsical. Suggestions in the *Communications of the ACM* included "turingineer," "turologist," and "applied meta-mathematician." &#91;42&#93; "Comptologist" and "hypologist" also made appearances. &#91;43&#93; In Europe, terms like *informatique* (French), *Informatik* (German), and *informatica* (Italian, Dutch) are common, often derived from translations of "automatic information" or "information and mathematics." &#91;45&#93; In the US, however, "informatics" tends to be more closely associated with applied computing.

There's a famous, often misattributed, quote, usually linked to [Edsger Dijkstra](/Edsger_Dijkstra): "computer science is no more about computers than astronomy is about telescopes." &#91;note 3&#93; It’s a sharp observation. The design and construction of computers are typically the domain of [computer engineering](/Computer_engineering), while the deployment of commercial systems falls under information technology or [information systems](/Information_system). Yet, the fields remain in constant dialogue. Computer science research also bleeds into and draws from [cognitive science](/Cognitive_science), [linguistics](/Computational_linguistics), [mathematics](/Mathematics), [physics](/Physics), [biology](/Biology), [Earth science](/Earth_science), [statistics](/Computational_statistics), [philosophy](/Philosophy), and [logic](/Logic).

Many consider computer science to be a mathematical science, given its deep roots in the work of mathematicians like [Kurt Gödel](/Kurt_G%C3%B6del), [Alan Turing](/Alan_Turing), and [John von Neumann](/John_von_Neumann). &#91;33&#93; This connection persists, with ongoing cross-pollination in areas like [mathematical logic](/Mathematical_logic), [category theory](/Category_theory), and [algebra](/Algebra). &#91;36&#93;

The relationship between computer science and [software engineering](/Software_engineering) is a perpetual source of debate. &#91;47&#93; Some, like [David Parnas](/David_Parnas), argue they are distinct but complementary: computer science explores the fundamental properties of computation, while software engineering focuses on the practical design of systems to achieve specific goals. &#91;48&#93;

The academic and funding landscape often depends on whether a department leans towards mathematics or engineering. Those with a mathematical bent might align more with [computational science](/Computational_science). Regardless, the goal is often to bridge these perspectives, both in education and research.

### Philosophy

*   Main article: [Philosophy of computer science](/Philosophy_of_computer_science)

#### Epistemology of Computer Science

Is computer science truly a *science*? A *mathematics* discipline? Or an *engineering* one? The debate is as old as the field itself. &#91;49&#93; &#91;50&#93; &#91;51&#93; [Allen Newell](/Allen_Newell) and [Herbert A. Simon](/Herbert_A._Simon) argued in 1975 that it is an empirical science, pointing to the construction and observation of machines as experiments. &#91;51&#93; However, defining the "laws" and "theorems" of computer science, and the nature of its experiments, remains a challenge.

Engineering proponents highlight the focus on reliability and robustness, drawing parallels to civil or aerospace engineering. &#91;51&#93; They argue that computer science creates phenomena, rather than merely discovering existing laws. Mathematical proponents, on the other hand, point to programs as physical manifestations of mathematical entities, amenable to deductive reasoning through [formal methods](/Formal_methods). &#91;51&#93; [Edsger Dijkstra](/Edsger_W._Dijkstra) and [Tony Hoare](/Tony_Hoare) famously viewed program instructions as mathematical statements, with formal semantics akin to [axiomatic systems](/Axiomatic_system). &#91;51&#93;

#### Paradigms of Computer Science

Some argue for distinct paradigms within computer science. [Peter Wegner](/Peter_Wegner_(computer_scientist)) identified science, technology, and mathematics. &#91;52&#93; [Peter Denning](/Peter_J._Denning)'s group proposed theory, abstraction (modeling), and design. &#91;33&#93; Amnon H. Eden further elaborated on this, describing a "rationalist paradigm" (mathematical), a "technocratic paradigm" (engineering), and a "scientific paradigm" (empirical, akin to natural sciences). &#91;54&#93;

At its core, computer science concerns itself with the methods of design, specification, programming, verification, implementation, and testing of human-made computing systems. &#91;55&#93;

### Fields

This is not an exhaustive list; the field is far too dynamic for that. But it gives you an idea of the sheer breadth.

As a discipline, computer science encompasses everything from the abstract limits of computation to the gritty reality of building systems. &#91;56&#93; &#91;57&#93; The [CSAB](/CSAB_(professional_organization)), a body comprising representatives from the [Association for Computing Machinery](/Association_for_Computing_Machinery) (ACM) and the [IEEE Computer Society](/IEEE_Computer_Society), identifies four crucial areas: theory of computation, algorithms and data structures, programming methodology and languages, and computer elements and architecture. They also acknowledge the importance of fields like software engineering, artificial intelligence, computer networking, database systems, parallel and distributed computation, human–computer interaction, computer graphics, operating systems, and numerical and [symbolic computation](/Symbolic_computation). &#91;56&#93;

#### Theoretical Computer Science

*   Main article: [Theoretical computer science](/Theoretical_computer_science)

This is the abstract, mathematical heart of the field. It’s where we ponder the fundamental nature of computation and strive for more efficient ways to achieve it, all while drawing inspiration from the practical demands of the digital world.

##### Theory of Computation

*   Main article: [Theory of computation](/Theory_of_computation)

The central question, as articulated by Peter Denning, is: "What can be automated?" &#91;3&#93; The theory of computation grapples with this, exploring what problems are solvable and what resources—time, space—are required. [Computability theory](/Computability_theory) investigates the boundaries of solvability across various theoretical [models of computation](/Models_of_computation), while [computational complexity theory](/Computational_complexity_theory) dissects the efficiency of different approaches.

The infamous [P = NP?](/P_%3D_NP%3F) problem, a cornerstone of this field, remains one of the great unsolved mysteries. &#91;59&#93;

